Step 1: KOtBu (strong, hindered base) effected an E2 elimination of the secondary alkyl bromide Ph–CH2–CH2–CH(Br)–CH3 to give the more substituted (Zaitsev) alkene A, Ph–CH2–CH=CH–CH3 (1-phenylbut-2-ene; a mixture of stereoisomers may be formed but the E2 is stereospecific for an anti elimination geometry available from the starting conformation).

Step 2: Hydroboration–oxidation (BH3·THF then H2O2/NaOH) is an anti‑Markovnikov, syn addition across the C=C of A, placing OH on the less substituted alkene carbon. That converts A into the secondary alcohol B: Ph–CH2–CH2–CH(OH)–CH3, whose preferred IUPAC name is 4-phenylbutan-2-ol. The OH-bearing carbon is stereogenic, so B is chiral (and will be formed as a single enantiomer only if the alkene stereochemistry was stereospecifically set; otherwise a racemate results).

Step 3: Treatment of the secondary alcohol B with PBr3 converts the alcohol into the corresponding alkyl bromide by an SN2 displacement (inversion of configuration at that stereocenter), giving the final product C: Ph–CH2–CH2–CH(Br)–CH3, i.e. 2-bromo-4-phenylbutane (IUPAC: 2-bromo-4-phenylbutane). The carbon bearing the bromine is a stereocenter; PBr3 inverts its configuration relative to the alcohol precursor B, so the stereochemical outcome of C (R or S) depends on the stereochemistry of B (and thus ultimately on the stereochemistry of the alkene formed in step 1).

Step 1: t-BuOK (bulky base) promotes E2 dehydrohalogenation of (3S)-3-bromobutylbenzene to give the Hofmann (less substituted) alkene A:
A = 4-phenylbut-1-ene (Ph–CH2–CH2–CH=CH2).

Step 2: Hydroboration–oxidation (BH3·THF then H2O2/NaOH) adds OH anti‑Markovnikov (B–H adds to the more substituted C, OH ends up on the less substituted carbon) with syn stereochemistry, converting the terminal alkene into the primary alcohol B:
B = 4-phenylbutan-1-ol (Ph–CH2–CH2–CH2–CH2OH).

Step 3: PBr3 converts the primary alcohol to the primary bromide via an SN2-type substitution, giving the final product C:
C = 1-bromo-4-phenylbutane (preferred IUPAC: 1-bromo-4-phenylbutane, same as 4-phenylbutyl bromide).

Chirality: the original (3S) stereocenter is lost in the elimination (A). B and C have no stereogenic center at the substituted carbon (primary carbon bearing OH or Br), so the final product C is achiral.

model_output:
Step 1 — E2 elimination (KOtBu, cyclohexane/Et2O):
The strong, non-nucleophilic base tert‑butoxide deprotonates a β‑hydrogen and the bromide leaves in an E2 process to give the more accessible (thermodynamically favored) internal alkene. The alkene A is therefore 1-phenyl-2-butene (Ph–CH2–CH=CH–CH3).

Step 2 — Hydroboration–oxidation (BH3·THF then H2O2/NaOH):
BH3 adds across the C=C in an anti‑Markovnikov, syn fashion: boron attaches to the less substituted carbon and hydrogen to the more substituted carbon. Oxidation (H2O2/OH−) converts the C–B bond to a C–OH bond, giving the alcohol B as 1-phenyl-3-butanol (Ph–CH2–CH2–CH(OH)–CH3). (This step creates the stereocenter at C‑3.)

Step 3 — Conversion of alcohol to bromide (PBr3):
PBr3 converts the secondary alcohol to the corresponding bromide by an SN2 mechanism, which inverts the configuration at the stereogenic carbon. Thus alcohol B is transformed into the bromide C with inversion.

Identity of C:
C is the enantiomer of the original bromide. In IUPAC form:
(R)-1‑phenyl‑3‑bromobutane
(or written as (R)-3-bromobutylbenzene).

Chirality explanation:
The sequence removes the original stereocenter (elimination to an achiral alkene) and then recreates a stereocenter during hydroboration–oxidation; the final PBr3 step is SN2 and inverts that newly formed stereocenter. Starting from (3S)-1‑phenyl‑3‑bromobutane the net result is (3R)-1‑phenyl‑3‑bromobutane.
